"{\"abstract\":\"Adversarial domain adaptation has been recently proposed as an effective technique for textual matching tasks, such as question deduplication. Here we investigate the use of gradient reversal on adversarial domain adaptation to explicitly learn both shared and unshared (domain specific) representations between two textual domains. In doing so, gradient reversal learns features that explicitly compensate for domain mismatch, while still distilling domain specific knowledge that can improve target domain accuracy. We evaluate reversing gradients for adversarial adaptation on multiple domains, and demonstrate that it significantly outperforms other methods on question deduplication as well as on recognizing textual entailment (RTE) tasks, achieving up to 7% absolute boost in base model accuracy on some datasets.\",\"arxivId\":null,\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":\"150017559\",\"name\":\"Anush Kamath\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/150017559\"},{\"authorId\":\"47925077\",\"name\":\"S. Gupta\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/47925077\"},{\"authorId\":\"145177235\",\"name\":\"Vitor R. Carvalho\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/145177235\"}],\"citationVelocity\":0,\"citations\":[{\"arxivId\":\"2010.07717\",\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":\"3313676\",\"name\":\"Wei-jie Yu\"},{\"authorId\":\"48258973\",\"name\":\"C. Xu\"},{\"authorId\":\"37184350\",\"name\":\"J. Xu\"},{\"authorId\":\"48537499\",\"name\":\"Liang Pang\"},{\"authorId\":\"49780034\",\"name\":\"Xiaopeng Gao\"},{\"authorId\":\"3251527\",\"name\":\"Xiaozhao Wang\"},{\"authorId\":\"153693432\",\"name\":\"Jirong Wen\"}],\"doi\":\"10.18653/v1/2020.emnlp-main.239\",\"intent\":[\"background\"],\"isInfluential\":false,\"paperId\":\"819aff442c5391235a3bb44b1133f37b50541601\",\"title\":\"Wasserstein Distance Regularized Sequence Representation for Text Matching in Asymmetrical Domains\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/819aff442c5391235a3bb44b1133f3